    <div class="container">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="text baljobbkeret">
                <div class="padder">
                    <p>Artificial stone v1.0</p>
                    In the previous step, we created truly beautiful artificial stones using nothing but ancient
                    materials — just waterglass and wood ash.
                    <br><br>
                    Yes, but the catch is that all these stones are grey, if not outright black.
                    <br><br>
                    True, wood ash is almost always gray,
                    and it turns the stone gray (or even black) as well.
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="image baljobbkeret" style="background-image: url('img/waterglass/kez.jpg');">
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row reverse">
            <div class="text baljobbkeret">
                <div class="padder">
                    <p>We need a transparent binder</p>

                    But ancient Egyptian stone objects come in every possible color. You can clearly see
                    the grains of the rock. So we’ll need some kind of transparent additive, not wood ash.
                    <br><br>
                    And the ingredient can’t be white either, because that would tint the stone white.
                    The grains have to remain visible.
                    <br><br>
                    What could it be?
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="image baljobbkeret" style="background-image: url('img/fake/sarco.jpg');">
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="text baljobbkeret">
                <div class="padder">
                    <p>Acids?</p>
                    Waterglass is alkaline. If you add any kind of acid to waterglass,
                    it precipitates silica gel — a completely transparent glue that hardens into stone
                    when exposed to air. It could be an ideal binder for creating artificial stone.
                    <br><br>
                    At least in theory. But no matter what acid I tried—hydrochloric acid, orange juice,
                    vinegar, etc.—the resulting stone didn’t resemble any natural stone.
                    Do you see this example? It’s like it’s made of jelly.
                    <br><br>
                    It is beautiful though, and the Nespresso capsule pressed into it gives it an extra charm.
                    But still...

                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="image baljobbkeret" style="background-image: url('img/fake/nespresso.jpg');"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="row reverse">
            <div class="text baljobbkeret">
                <div class="padder">
                    <p>Alcohol?</p>
                    Alcohols also immediately precipitate the silica gel from waterglass, and for a long time
                    I thought alcohol would be the ultimate solution—after all, it’s good for hangovers,
                    so why wouldn’t it work here?
                    <br><br>
                    In the video, we can see how the silica gel instantly separates from the waterglass
                    when an alcoholic drink is added. However, even the alcoholic gel didn’t produce a stone that
                    resembled a natural one.
                    <br><br>
                    Okay, what else?
                </div>
            </div>
            <div id="videobackground" class=" baljobbkeret">
                <video autoplay loop muted playsinline src="img/fake/spirit.mp4" poster="img/fake/spirit.jpg"
                    type="video/mp4"></video>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="text baljobbkeret">
                <div class="padder">
                    <p>A base?</p>
                    But we’ve already crossed bases off the list, since bases don’t destabilize waterglass.
                    I won’t beat around the bush—even though it took me two years—the secret additive is a base.
                    <br><br>
                    Specifically, slaked lime, but in a very small, 2% dosage, added as a catalyst only.
                    See, it’s alkaline, so in theory it shouldn’t work at all, and it’s white, so it’s not
                    transparent—but by the time the material sets, it becomes clear.
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="image baljobbkeret" style="background-image: url('img/fake/slakedlime.jpg');">
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row reverse">
            <div class="text baljobbkeret">
                <div class="padder">
                    <p>Artificial fake granite</p>
                    And this is what the final result looks like. This beautiful cast stone isn’t even
                    made from granite rubble, but from plain quartz sand. The ultimate appearance, of course,
                    depends on the type of ground stone—if it’s lemon yellow or mottled, the stone will look the same.
                    <br><br>
                    The binder is transparent. Oh, and it’s hard—Mohs 6–6.5. Oh, and it has the same chemical
                    composition as quartz: SiO₂.
                </div>
            </div>
            <div id="videobackground" class=" baljobbkeret">
                <video autoplay loop muted playsinline src="img/fake/sajatko.mp4" poster="img/fake/sajatko.jpg"
                    type="video/mp4"></video>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="text baljobbkeret">
                <div class="padder">
                    <p>But where did the crushed granite come from?</p>
                    The usual naysayer complaint is always, ‘How did the Egyptians produce all that crushed granite?’
                    I’ll tell you.
                    They didn’t. Around Aswan, on the east bank of the Nile, there’s a stone desert.<br><br>
                    More precisely: a desert of granite rubble. Yeah. Where even the sand is not sand but crushed
                    granite. Yeah.
                    The pink area is.
                    All you need is a shovel and a broom...
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="image baljobbkeret" style="background-image: url('img/fake/aswanmap.jpg');">
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row reverse">
            <div class="text baljobbkeret">
                <div class="padder">
                    <p>And the slaked lime?</p>
                    Slaked lime is so old-school, it’s been passed around longer than the village gossip.
                    Even cavemen were already using it. Or Adam himself, probably.
                    <br><br>
                    How do we know? Easy, anyone wrapping themselves in animal hides is rocking tanned leather,
                    and step one of tanning is soaking the skin in lime putty.
                    So yeah, if you wanted some, you had to pop next door and borrow a cup from the neighborhood tanner.
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="image baljobbkeret" style="background-image: url('img/fake/cser.jpeg');">
            </div>
        </div>
